english:
  title: A Letter to Lee, Minister of Justice
  author: Im Chun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I bow my head and prostrate myself twice, offering this letter to you, Minister of Justice of the Penal Bureau.

    I have heard that the valley of Yan lies thousands of miles from the Middle Kingdom—so distant that none can measure it. Yet the great warmth of heaven nurtures all things equally, whether near or far. And yet, in that land alone, millet refuses to grow. Truly, it is one forsaken hollow of creation.

    There was one called Zou Yan who played the pipes within that valley and warmed it. Then a single spark of harmony descended from the Great Void, and all things flourished. Spring came forth in gentle warmth.

    Alas! Zou Yan brought spring to the barren valley between heaven and earth. And you, my lord, have brought spring to the impoverished people between heaven and earth.

    I humbly reflect that you possess the virtue of a True Man. Your joy and anger harmonize with the four seasons—sorrowful as autumn when you grieve, warm as spring when you comfort. When you blow cold, all withers; when you breathe warm, all blossoms. Many are those who have basked in your grace.

    As for myself, I am a son of humble birth, born in regions of frost and shadow, my face weathered and dull-featured, bearing the countenance of ice and snow. My body is broken, my household ruined. Poverty dogs my steps; many mouths depend on scanty rice. Pressed by want, I journeyed east, living by beggary for five long years. This spring I returned to official service, yet still I wander like a guest, my stores depleted. My frail wife and widowed sister are scattered like tumbleweed and duckweed—one lost at the edge of heaven, one at the corner of earth. We possess not a single plot or dwelling where we might gather and find shelter. When I think upon this, tears flow unbidden.

    My ancestors once served in the age of chaos, earning glory through loyal service. Their likenesses were painted in the Hall of Heroes; they received scrolls of red silk and iron seals granting them lands forever. Yet these were seized by soldiers. Now I cannot even find an acre beyond the walls, and I cannot write the verse of Tao Yuanming's "Return."

    I have never rubbed shoulders with wise men, nor do my name known in the chambers of nobles. Now I come bearing a long letter, writing out my wanderer's sorrow with brushstrokes of urgent plea, crying out boldly for pity from those above. Not only do others laugh at me—I laugh at myself. Yet to clothe the unrewarded and bestow virtue on the undeserving requires a heart of supreme goodness and perfect benevolence—no ordinary task. In all this world, only you, my lord, are worthy of such hopes. Therefore I dare speak my sorrow without shame.

    I earnestly beseech you: lift up the impoverished kindred, restrain the grasping wealthy, restore the collapsing order in these declining days. Judge our case and render justice. Grant me return to those desolate ancestral fields. Then my entire household—all ten souls—shall pass from hunger and cold at dawn to fullness and warmth by evening. Would this not be the very miracle wrought in the crucible of your compassionate heart? Is this not bringing spring to those in winter's grip?

    I dare not presume, and my reverence knows no bounds. I bow twice before you.
  footnotes:
    - Zou Yan (鄒衍) was a legendary sage who allegedly used harmonic resonance to transform the climate of barren lands—a reference to the power of virtue to transform circumstances.
    - The Hall of Heroes (凌煙閣) was where portraits of meritorious officials and generals were displayed, symbolizing lasting honor and official recognition.
    - Tao Yuanming's (陶淵明) "Return" (歸去來) is a famous poem about withdrawal from official life to agricultural simplicity—something the author cannot achieve due to his dispossession.
